Gene Wolfe says the essence of communication is smell. Early men and women did not talk too much, as pheromones said all about one's state and feeling in the moment. After fire's fumes dulled their noses through some colder centuries, speech became necessary to fill the new gaps.

A man can smell if a woman is in love with him. But if there is distance, she might write him a letter of love, and perfume the letter. The perfume is not the odor of her body's desire, but an artificial simulation of it. Your love is for a whale sperm, male deer musk, rose oils.

Touch is the most basic, extended through space as smell (taste is simply touching a smell). When smell is blocked, sound recreates and simulates it. When sound is blocked, writing (sight) recreates and simulates it. A pefume is not what she feels, but what she tells she feels.
